Motivation and Background¶

Give an overview of the project, motivation, background and goals.

The project is about analysing the popularity of amusement parks, mainly how it was affected by the pandemic. There have definitely been impacts to the amusement parks, but by how much? That is the question I wish to analyse. The motivation behind this project was visiting an amusement for the first time since the pandemic struck, and realising that there were already many people there, so I wanted to know how and when people started coming back. The goal is to have a better understanding of how badly the pandemic affecting the amusement parks and how they have recovered.

Summary of Research Questions & Results¶

Repeat your research questions in a numbered list. After each research question, clearly state the answer/conclusion you determined. Do not give details or justifications yet — just the answer

  1. Based on the attendance data, was there an increasing trend in the attendance prior to the pandemic? And when the pandemic struck, how drastic was the decrease in attendance?

    Answer: There was a steady increase in general before the pandemic. In 2020, the median drop was around 1/3 of the previous year.

  2. When did the effects of the pandemic strike? How quickly did amusement parks recover from the pandemic? Did the number of days a park was open for revert to the original number, or was it still affected by the pandemic?

    Answer: 2020 had the worst effects from the pandemic, and in 2021, parks have already restored the number of days open back to the norm. The effect of the pandemic was the worst from April to May 2020, and from July, most parks have already reopened.

Dataset¶

Numbered list of dataset (with downloadable links) and a brief but clear description of each dataset used. Draw reference to the numbering when describing methodology (data cleaning and analysis).

  1. https://aecom.com: There are theme indexes listing the top 25 amusement parks from 2012 onwards, including the percentage change in attendance.

  2. https://queue-times.com: The data on this site shows the relative crowd level for each park for each day.

Methodology¶

You should demonstrate the data science life cycle here (from data acquisition to cleaning to EDA and analysis etc).

Data Acquisition:¶

Scraping from https://aecom.com: There are theme indexes listing the top 25 amusement parks from 2012 onwards. I will be scraping all the data using tabula.py. This is a python library that is able to read pdfs and convert them into pandas dataframes.

Scraping from https://queue-times.com: The data on this site shows the relative crowd level for each park for each day. This is in terms of a percentage. When there is no data available, the park is closed on that day. Data for 2016 to 2021 was scraped for each day for each park which has a "Calendar" page on the site. This was done via python requests.

Data Cleaning:¶

Data from https://aecom.com in general had very different formatting across different years. Tabula.py would also read multilined names from the pdf as separate rows in the data frames, so these extra unnecessary lines would need to be cleaned off. Afterwards, the Change and Current data are extracted into 2 DataFrames called merged_change and merged respectively, to be used in the EDA section.

Raw data from https://queue-times.com did not require cleaning past the data acquisition. However, I filtered out the useful data by considering which parks were open since a certain point, so that there would be less NA's.

EDA:¶

For the first dataset, I created multiple visualisations using different types of graphs. In general, they are able to show that there is an increasing trend from 2012 through 2019, and show the sharp decrease in 2020. Some visualisations are able to show trends of the highest and lowest in the top 25, while others show the spread of the data.

For the second dataset, from the data cleaning, parks are filtered from if they are open in 2016 and if they are open in 2019, giving 2 different sets of parks, with corresponding data in open16 and open19. The data from these is then placed into a heatmap, and similarly month2020 which shows the percentage of days open in 2020 by month is put into a heatmap too.

Results Findings and Conclusion¶

For question 1, trends were observed from the joyplot of the percentage change, and the boxenplot of the attendance over the years.

For question 2, the heatmaps with varying data input are analysed.

Data Cleaning¶

For data cleaning, be clear in which dataset (or variables) are used, what has been done for missing data, how was merging performed, explanation of data transformation (if any). If data is calculated or summarized from the raw dataset, explain the rationale and steps clearly.

Dataset 1¶

The following are the data cleaning steps taken to clean dataset 1. In general, the Current and Previous have commas removed and converted to ints, Change has percentage sign removed and converted to float; other necessary cleaning is in the comment of the respective cell.

#df2012 cleaning: fix multi-line names
df2012.loc[:,"Change"] = df2012.Change.fillna(method="bfill").str.replace('[%]','',regex=True).astype('float64')
df2012.loc[:,"Previous"] = df2012.Previous.fillna(method="bfill").fillna(method="ffill").str.replace('[*,]','',regex=True).astype('int64')
df2012.loc[:,"Current"] = df2012.Current.fillna(method="bfill").fillna(method="ffill").str.replace('[*,]','',regex=True).astype('int64')
df2012 = df2012[::3]

1. Based on the attendance data, was there an increasing trend in the attendance prior to the pandemic? And when the pandemic struck, how drastic was the decrease in attendance?¶

From the boxenplot, there is a clear increasing trend in the attendance from 2012 through 2019. While the top 25th amusement park by attendance has roughly constant attendance, the median and maximum are increasing in general. The spread is also increasing.

In 2020, the attendance dropped significantly. The percentage change is more apparent in the joyplot: for years 2012 through 2019, the percentage change hovered slightly over 0%, except for two outliers above 50% which have been removed from the visualisation for the purpose of clarity. However, in 2020, the percentage change has a median of -66.9%, which is a drop to less than a third of the previous year (2019).

2. When did the effects of the pandemic strike? How quickly did amusement parks recover from the pandemic? Did the number of days a park was open for revert to the original number, or was it still affected by the pandemic?¶

From the 2016 and 2019 graphs, it is clear that in general, 2020 had the worst effects from the pandemic. While there have been some slight deviations within the other years, the decrease in number of days open in 2020 is apparent from the different shades in 2020 for each column.

Seeing from the graph of percentage of days open, the effect of the pandemic was worst from April to May of 2020, where almost all parks were fully closed. In June, around half of the parks were still closed. Then from July onward, most parks which opened in 2020 have already reopened, and by August they were almost open similar at rates similar to before. There was also closure in November, which I have insufficient information to deduce whether the closure is because of the pandemic or not.

In addition, looking at the 2019 graph, the colour scheme of the year 2021 is very similar to that of 2019, apart from a few parks which might just be having other improvements over the years. But this highlights the fact that parks have restored their opening days back to the original number for the most part.
